      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>With his Middle East speech (front page, June 25), President Bush has left many Israelis more aware of America's lack of an explicit policy.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>With his Middle East speech (front page, June 25), President Bush has left many Israelis more aware of America's lack of an explicit policy.</p>
        <p>Many Israeli citizens would welcome a more explicit and directive American policy, which would allow all parties to save political face.</p>
        <p>Prime Minister Ariel Sharon's government has interpreted Mr. Bush's speech as giving it space to carry out its policy. But many Israelis have quietly interpreted the lack of directive in the speech as abandoning them and the Palestinians to an endless, self-destructive spiral of conflict.</p>
        <p>SAMUEL B. BACHARACH  Haifa, Israel, June 25, 2002</p>
      </block>
